const items = [
  {
    id:       'meridian',
    category: 'PROJECT',
    title:    'Meridian',
    meta:     'React + TypeScript · 2024',
    body: [
      'Meridian is a usage-analytics dashboard for a B2B SaaS product — the kind of internal tool that starts as a spreadsheet and slowly turns into the thing the whole company checks every morning. The brief was to make that transition without the rebuild taking six months.',
      'The hardest part was rendering thousands of data points without the UI stuttering. Virtualising the table and moving the heavier chart aggregation off the main thread with a Web Worker turned a visibly janky scroll into a smooth one — the kind of fix that never shows up in a screenshot but is the difference between a tool people tolerate and one they trust.',
      'Shipped and in daily use by the product team since launch. The lesson that carried forward: performance work on internal tools is invisible right up until it is missing.',
    ],
    topics: ['The Brief', 'The Hard Part', 'The Outcome'],
  },
  {
    id:       'northwind',
    category: 'PROJECT',
    title:    'Northwind',
    meta:     'Astro + Node.js · 2024',
    body: [
      'Northwind is a headless e-commerce rebuild — same product catalogue and checkout logic, moved off a heavyweight monolith and onto a static-first Astro front end with a lightweight Node API behind it. The goal was speed: the old storefront was losing mobile shoppers to load time before they ever saw a product.',
      'The constraint was migrating without downtime and without breaking the client\'s existing inventory sync. That meant running both systems in parallel behind a feature flag for three weeks, comparing outputs field-by-field before the old storefront was retired.',
      'Time-to-interactive dropped from a little over four seconds to under one on mobile. Concrete numbers over adjectives: that was the whole point of the rebuild.',
    ],
    topics: ['Why Rebuild', 'The Constraint', 'The Numbers'],
  },
  {
    id:       'pulsegrid',
    category: 'PROJECT',
    title:    'Pulsegrid',
    meta:     'Three.js + WebGL · 2023',
    body: [
      'Pulsegrid is a real-time data-visualisation layer for IoT sensor networks — hundreds of live data points rendered as an interactive 3D field rather than a table of numbers, so an operator can spot an anomaly by shape, not by scanning rows.',
      'This is the project that shows the range beyond typical CRUD/dashboard work: shader-driven visuals, WebSocket-fed live data, and a rendering loop that has to stay smooth even as the dataset grows mid-session.',
      'It is also the direct predecessor to this planetarium\'s own custom shader-graph system — Pulsegrid was where the itch to build proper 3D tooling instead of hand-rolling one-off GLSL first showed up.',
    ],
    topics: ['The Concept', 'Showing Range', 'Where It Led'],
  },
  {
    id:       'open-source',
    category: 'OPEN SOURCE',
    title:    'In the Commons',
    meta:     'Contributions & published tools',
    body: [
      'Strata is a CSS utility framework built and maintained from scratch — it powers every page on this site, including this one. It exists because utility-class frameworks kept forcing tradeoffs (arbitrary-value support, cascade-layer discipline, dark-mode tokens) that felt worth solving properly rather than working around.',
      'Triforge is a Blender-style shader-graph system for Three.js — the node-based tool that renders every planet material, the warp transition, and the landing-page carousel on this site. It exists because hand-writing GLSL for nine different planet materials did not scale, and no existing library offered a node graph built specifically for Three.js.',
      'Both are public on GitHub and under active development — this site is the largest real-world proving ground for both, and bugs found while building it get fixed upstream in the packages, not patched around locally.',
    ],
    topics: ['Strata', 'Triforge', 'Built From Real Use'],
  },
];
